interfac","introduct","is,","japan)","job","k50","khoa","kid","know,","larg","last","lead","learn","length","let'","level.","linux,","list","live","local","logic","logic,","long","look","love","machin","machine,","maintain","make","mani","marathon","marri","master","mean","mechan","mechanisms.","mechatron","messag","message,","message.","miller","monitor","month","more","more.","motion","motobik","mountain","mountain,","move","much","nang","need","needs.","network","network)","newyork","ngothtam.me@gmail.comlinkedin","nhon","normally,","number","octet","open","over","page","parser","part","phan","phandung,","place","plc,","posibl","prepar","printer","program","project","protocol","protocols,","provinc","queri","queueing)","quy","read","realli","receiv","recov","remot","respons","rest","right","robot","rust,","same","scale","see","send","sent","server","shop","simpler,","singleton,","sip","sip,","skills:","skydiv","so,","softwar","someon","someth","soon","sourc","speak","start","state","stock","streams,","struct","support","swim","switch","system","system.","systems.","ta","take","talk","tam,","tanang","tcp","tcp,","tcp.","teach","team","ted","telecom","tell","teppanyaki","thank","that'","thing","those","time","transfer","udp","udp.","udp/tcp","understand","univers","unsign","us","vacat","veri","vietnam","visit","vs","wait","want","waterfal","waterfall)","way","websit","went","wood","work","world","wrong.","year","year,","years,","youtub","✓","✗","❤","😊"],"pipeline":["stopWordFilter","stemmer"]},"store":{"./":{"url":"./","title":"Introduction","keywords":"","body":"Hello\n\nI'm Tam, a software engineer. I like coding, hiking, and beaches. Currently, I'm interested in C++, Golang, Rust, and system designs.\nI graduated from Bach Khoa university as an mechatronics engineer. I had worked as a part-time automation engineer from 3rd year for 1.5 years, and 6 more months as a full time engineer. Most of work were to program PLC, 6-axis robot controllers, and motion controllers. I also collaborate with mechanical and electrical teams to design and assemble automation systems.\nAfter 2 years in automation industry, I switched my career to software engineering. The first year, I worked in telecom industry, with a very large-scaled distributed system. Most of my daily jobs were to develop and maintain SIP framework, caching, blacklisting, and network monitoring mechanisms. The last 4 months at the same company, I worked as a customer support engineer, the most important responsibility was to help customers to recover live systems as soon as posible when something went wrong. I also answered queries from customers from all over the world about system configuration, architectures, and behaviors.\nSome of my skills:\n\nC++,\nSIP, DNS protocols\nUDP/TCP (socket handover, framing, queueing)\nSingleton, state machine, caching\nLinux, git\n\nProjects\nMost of my projects are on github\n\nDNS client\nDNS server\nStock crawler\nAlgorithms\n\nSome beautiful places in Vietnam I have visited\n\nTa Nang Phan Dung\nChua Chan mountain\nK50 waterfall\nQuy Nhon Beach\n\nContacts\nngothtam.me@gmail.comlinkedin\n"},"dns_client/":{"url":"dns_client/","title":"DNS client","keywords":"","body":"DNS UDP vs TCP\nNormally, DNS message would be sent over UDP protocols, this is because UDP is much faster than TCP, and that's all DNS needs. DNS is not a so important information that should be transfered by TCP.\nUsing UDP instead of TCP makes implementation much simpler, DNS client does not need to maintain the connection, just send and wait for response (or expect a callback if you are using async network)\nAnother thing about using UDP and TCP is in message format. As you may know, using TCP means you need to prepare to handle fragmented message, you may have to deal with TCP framing, because TCP uses streams, not datagram as in UDP. This leads to the DNS message must be indicated how long it is, this is done by 2 octets form a 16-bit unsigned int to tells the receiver how many byte it need to way to receive more.\nBoth encoder and parser needs to deal with difference in DNS format between UDP and TCP, encoder needs to add a 2 octets number to indicate the length of the message in case of TCP, and the receiver needs to read those 2 octets first to prepare to read the rest of the message.\nLet's take a look closer at the implementation, you can distinguish the difference in the encoder or parser logic, but if you do so, the interface to the constructor of message class or struct would be more complicated. Instead, you can move the logic that handles difference between message formats to right above the network level.\nThanks for reading\n"},"bucket_list/":{"url":"bucket_list/","title":"Bucket list","keywords":"","body":"Things I want to do before I die\n\n    ❤ Be happy\n    ✗ Live at a beach\n    ✗ Start a company\n    ✗ Get married\n    ✗ Have kids\n    ✗ Buy a electric car\n    ✗ Work remotely (once, but because of covid-19)\n    ✗ Live in another country (Singapore, Europe, Japan)\n    ✗ See aurora\n    ✗ Start a company\n    ✗ Speak at TED talk\n    ✗ Fall in love\n    ✓ Become an engineer (mechatronics, software engineer)\n    ✗ Become a good engineer\n    ✓ Graduate college\n    ✗ Graduate master program\n    ✗ Go diving\n    ✗ Go skydiving\n    ✓ Go hiking (chua chan mountain, tanang-phandung, K50 waterfall)\n    ✗ Buy a house\n    ✗ Go on a helicoper\n    ✗ Have a classic motobike\n    ✗ Vacation on a cruise shop\n    ✗ Dinner at a Teppanyaki beefsteak\n    ✗ Visit Newyork\n    ✗ Visit all 63 provinces in Vietnam with a motobike\n    ✗ Understand someone\n    ✗ Learn to swim\n    ✗ Teach my kids to program 😊\n    ✗ Build a 3D printer\n    ✗ Build a wood miller\n    ✓ Have my own website\n    ✗ Contribute to open-source projects\n    ✗ Start a open-source project that has contributors\n    ✓ get really really really drunk\n    ✗ complete 42km marathon\n    ✗ hike fansipan\n"},"local/":{"url":"local/","title":"Local",